e1ab0-3 | 2026-06-05T15:40:29Z | session:e1ab0629-64bc-4383-bd22-c0843ca16a99 | - **App backgrounded or killed** → *neither* restarts. Both use a **background `URLSession`**, so iOS's download daemon keeps transferring even while the app is suspended or terminated. Progress is not lost. \n - **Network drop / transport failure, or an explicit Cancel** → this is where they diverge: \n  \n **Episodes — yes, they resume from where they stopped.** `DownloadCapability` captures the OS's resume blob (`NSURLSessionDownloadTaskResumeData`) on failure, pause, and cancel, persists it to disk (`…/resumeData/<episode>.data`), and on the next start calls `downloadTask(withResumeData:)` — continuing from the saved byte offset instead of byte 0 (`DownloadCapability.swift:224`). Pause explicitly produces resume data via `cancel(byProducingResumeData:)`. Standard caveat: if the server doesn't honor range requests or the partial data is invalidated, URLSession silently falls back to a full restart. \n  \n **Models — no, a real interruption restarts from scratch.** `LocalModelDownloadManager.download()` always creates `session.downloadTask(with: request)` — it never uses `withResumeData:`. And its error handler just logs and sets `.notDownloaded`; it **never captures or persists the resume blob**. So on a genuine network failure (or Cancel), the next Download tap starts the 2.6–3.8 GB file over from 0. (Backgrounding/killing the app is still fine — the OS keeps going.) [...] On iOS, **the byte transfer must stay in the platform executor**, not Rust. Only a background-configured `URLSession` keeps downloading while the app is suspended/terminated and relaunches it on completion — essential for 2.6–3.8 GB model files. Rust running in-process is frozen the moment iOS suspends the app, so a pure-Rust transfer would *lose* the background capability both current paths rely on. (Android: same story via DownloadManager/WorkManager.) \n  \n So "centralize in Rust" = centralize the **brain** (queue, dedup, priority, retry, resume bookkeeping, disk-space checks, wifi gating, the canonical "what's downloaded" record). The **socket** stays per-platform. That's already the episode architecture. [...] **Episodes — yes, they resume from where they stopped.** `DownloadCapability` captures the OS's resume blob (`NSURLSessionDownloadTaskResumeData`) on failure, pause, and cancel, persists it to disk (`…/resumeData/<episode>.data`), and on the next start calls `downloadTask(withResumeData:)` — continuing from the saved byte offset instead of byte 0 (`DownloadCapability.swift:224`). Pause explicitly produces resume data via `cancel(byProducingResumeData:)`. Standard caveat: if the server doesn't honor range requests or the partial data is invalidated, URLSession silently falls back to a full restart. \n  \n **Models — no, a real interruption restarts from scratch.** `LocalModelDownloadManager.download()` always creates `session.downloadTask(with: request)` — it never uses `withResumeData:`. And its error handler just logs and sets `.notDownloaded`; it **never captures or persists the resume blob**. So on a genuine network failure (or Cancel), the next Download tap starts the 2.6–3.8 GB file over from 0. (Backgrounding/killing the app is still fine — the OS keeps going.) \n  \n So the model path has a real gap, especially painful at multi-GB sizes. The episode code already has the exact pattern to copy (persist resume data on failure → `downloadTask(withResumeData:)` on retry).
e1ab0-4 | 2026-06-05T15:40:29Z | session:e1ab0629-64bc-4383-bd22-c0843ca16a99 | **Swift**: generalize `DownloadCapability` — `destinationURL(for:sourceURL:kind:)` (Episode → `Downloads/<id>.<ext>`, LocalModel → `LocalModels/<id>.litertlm`), resume keyed by kind, and `taskDescription` prefixed `model:<id>` only for models (episodes keep bare id → backward compatible). Delete `LocalModelDownloadManager`; model state comes from the kernel download snapshot (in-flight) + file-on-disk (downloaded); rewire `syncLocalEngine`/`LocalLLMService`/model UI to a shared `LocalModels/<id>.litertlm` path helper. \n  \n Let me validate this with the advisor before writing it. [...] Assistant: I'll generalize storage with kind-aware variants (keeping episode-default wrappers so untouched callers stay byte-identical), and add a public `localModelFileURL` helper matching the old path exactly: \n  \n Assistant: Now the main capability — thread `kind` through start + encode it into `taskDescription`. Let me read the relevant section: \n  \n Assistant: I'll thread `kind` through and encode it into `taskDescription` (bare id for episodes = back-compat; `local_model:<id>` for models). First `execute` + `startDownload`: [...] There was one root cause behind all three symptoms you described. When a model download finished, the code tried to figure out *which* model just completed by comparing the **on-disk** filename (`gemma4-e2b`) against the **remote URL** filename (`gemma-4-E2B-it`). Those are never equal, so the match always failed and the code bailed out early — **the downloaded file was never moved into place**: \n  \n - **Stuck at 100%** — progress hit 1.0, but the "move file + mark downloaded" step silently aborted, so the row never advanced. \n - **"Download" after restart** — nothing was ever written to disk, so on relaunch the app correctly saw no file. \n - **"Cancel" with no percentage on retry** — a separate lifecycle bug: the download manager was rebuilt every time you opened the Local Models screen, which leaks the old background session (iOS only allows one per identifier) and leaves the visible screen wired to a manager that no longer receives progress callbacks. \n  \n I also found that the app told iOS "background download done" *prematurely* for the model session (it routed those events to the unrelated episode-download system), which can let iOS suspend the app mid-finalization of a multi-GB file. \n  \n Fixes: match by download URL (the correct, consistent approach), make the manager a single shared instance, route the model session's background events to it properly, and keep in-flight downloads from flickering back to "Download." Verified by a full app **build + link succeeding** and a standalone proof that the old matching produced NO MATCH while the new one resolves correctly. Added a regression test. (Full on-simulator XCTest is blocked by a pre-existing, unrelated dylib/infra issue — detailed honestly in the PR.)
