deb49-7 | 2026-06-06T00:57:07Z | session:deb49f4f-f275-419a-ab1c-b68c123af73b | The architecture is: Rust is SSOT, bumps a `rev` atomic on every change, and Swift pulls a snapshot across the FFI. The expensive part is the *shape of that snapshot*. `nmp_app_podcast_snapshot()` serializes the **entire** `PodcastUpdate` — every podcast × every episode with ~30 fields each (`snapshot.rs:35-378`) — into one **JSON string**, hands the C string across, and Swift `JSONDecoder`-decodes the whole library back (`KernelBridge+Callbacks.swift:262-279`). That happens whenever content changes, up to 4 Hz during playback. With 3,615 episodes that's a large allocate-serialize-copy-decode every tick. That's exactly your memory note `perf_snapshot_decode_hotpath`: "every kernel rev bump = full JSON decode + O(N) hashes on the main thread." [...] - **Rust:** `snapshot_cache` returns cached JSON when `rev` is unchanged (`snapshot.rs:380-400`); a **separate narrow** `downloads_rev`/`downloads_snapshot` so the 1 Hz progress stream never pays the full-library cost (`snapshot.rs:447-489`). [...] - **KernelModel:** `lastProcessedRev` drops redundant frames; content hashes (`libraryMetaHash`/`snapshotContentHash`) that **exclude** volatile position/buffering so lists don't re-render at 4 Hz; the O(N×M) hashing is moved **off-MainActor** via `Task.detached` on the push path; `nowPlaying`/`downloadSnapshot` are separate observation targets so position updates don't churn lists. [...] - **Projection:** `libraryGeneration` gives an **O(1) fast path** that skips the entire episode rebuild when only the snapshot/identity changed; summary-level diff so only *changed* episodes pay `toEpisode`.
